1
00:00:01,241 --> 00:00:02,441
BILL: So...
DOCTOR: So...

2
00:00:02,721 --> 00:00:03,881
What do we do?

3
00:00:04,041 --> 00:00:06,721
Do I have to to sit somewhere?
Are there seat belts? Like...

4
00:00:07,001 --> 00:00:09,561
What? You've done this before.
This isn't your first trip.

5
00:00:09,881 --> 00:00:11,801
Yeah, but it's proper this time.

6
00:00:13,401 --> 00:00:14,521
Oh, that's a mistake.

7
00:00:14,601 --> 00:00:15,721
What is?

8
00:00:15,841 --> 00:00:17,401
BILL: Well, you can't reach the controls
from the seats,

9
00:00:17,481 --> 00:00:19,001
what's the point in that?

10
00:00:19,321 --> 00:00:21,321
Or do you have stretchy arms
like Mr Fantastic?

11
00:00:21,401 --> 00:00:23,841
Oh, I stand. Like this.

12
00:00:24,081 --> 00:00:26,641
You never thought of bringing
the seats a bit closer?

13
00:00:26,761 --> 00:00:27,921
No, not so far, no.

14
00:00:28,601 --> 00:00:29,961
(GASPS) Where's the steering wheel?

15
00:00:30,401 --> 00:00:33,321
Well, you don't steer the TARDIS,

16
00:00:34,081 --> 00:00:35,681
you negotiate with it.

17
00:00:37,401 --> 00:00:40,801
Still point between where you want to go

18
00:00:40,881 --> 00:00:42,281
and where you need to be.

19
00:00:42,481 --> 00:00:43,961
That's where she takes you.

20
00:00:44,161 --> 00:00:45,601
How much did it cost?

21
00:00:45,801 --> 00:00:46,921
DOCTOR: Ah.

22
00:00:48,201 --> 00:00:49,361
No idea.

23
00:00:50,001 --> 00:00:51,001
Stole it.

24
00:00:53,121 --> 00:00:54,561
-Seriously?
-Yeah.

25
00:00:54,921 --> 00:00:56,321
(CHUCKLES) Why?

26
00:00:57,161 --> 00:00:58,641
Well, actually, because I felt like it.

27
00:00:58,721 --> 00:00:59,841
Oh, what if I steal it from you?

28
00:01:00,121 --> 00:01:01,401
On you go, then.

29
00:01:02,161 --> 00:01:03,401
(LAUGHS) Well,
I don't know how it works.

30
00:01:03,881 --> 00:01:05,201
Oh, neither did I.

31
00:01:05,281 --> 00:01:06,881
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

32
00:01:07,521 --> 00:01:08,641
Who's that?

33
00:01:09,641 --> 00:01:11,321
(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

34
00:01:11,881 --> 00:01:13,041
(WHISPERS) Mum.

35
00:01:17,081 --> 00:01:18,681
-(CLEARS THROAT)
-NARDOLE: Excuse me.

36
00:01:19,401 --> 00:01:21,401
Just what is the TARDIS doing down here?

37
00:01:21,481 --> 00:01:23,001
I'm over 2,000 years old.

38
00:01:23,081 --> 00:01:24,561
I don't always want to take the stairs.

39
00:01:24,641 --> 00:01:26,001
Your oath, sir.

40
00:01:26,081 --> 00:01:28,841
You're not supposed to go off-world
unless it's an emergency.

41
00:01:28,921 --> 00:01:31,081
-I'm not off-world.
-Are you going off-world?

42
00:01:31,201 --> 00:01:32,321
I'm going back to my office.

43
00:01:34,001 --> 00:01:35,481
Could you put the kettle on, please?

44
00:01:35,841 --> 00:01:36,841
Mmm.

45
00:01:39,041 --> 00:01:40,281
Why's she here?

46
00:01:40,801 --> 00:01:43,281
DOCTOR: Because she isn't
anywhere else.

47
00:01:44,121 --> 00:01:45,401
Kettle.

48
00:01:45,681 --> 00:01:46,681
(NARDOLE GRUMBLES)

49
00:01:47,321 --> 00:01:49,361
I'm not making any for her.
She can make her own.

50
00:01:49,441 --> 00:01:51,961
Not a slave for a human,
I can assure you.

51
00:01:52,921 --> 00:01:53,921
(DOOR CLOSES)

52
00:01:57,201 --> 00:01:58,201
So...

53
00:02:00,841 --> 00:02:02,041
Back up to your office
for a cuppa, then?

54
00:02:04,161 --> 00:02:05,361
Between here and my office,

55
00:02:05,881 --> 00:02:07,561
before the kettle boils,

56
00:02:07,641 --> 00:02:09,721
is everything that ever happened
or ever will.

57
00:02:11,401 --> 00:02:13,281
-Make your choice.
-What choice?

58
00:02:14,721 --> 00:02:15,961
Past or future.

59
00:02:17,281 --> 00:02:18,281
Future.

60
00:02:19,921 --> 00:02:21,121
(BEEPING)

61
00:02:22,281 --> 00:02:23,281
Why?

62
00:02:23,481 --> 00:02:25,761
Why do you think?
I want to see if it's happy.

63
00:02:26,841 --> 00:02:28,161
(WHOOSHING)

64
00:02:31,001 --> 00:02:33,601
GOODTHING: (ON INTERCOM)
Kezzia, where are you?

65
00:02:35,361 --> 00:02:37,841
Hey, Goodthing. I'm coming back in.

66
00:02:37,961 --> 00:02:39,401
GOODTHING: Kezzia,
don't come in just yet.

67
00:02:39,721 --> 00:02:41,401
KEZZIA: I've been out
since second sunrise.

68
00:02:41,481 --> 00:02:42,681
I'm hungry.

69
00:02:43,641 --> 00:02:45,401
Round them up, big fella.

70
00:02:51,561 --> 00:02:53,401
GOODTHING: Kezzia, please don't come in.

71
00:02:53,481 --> 00:02:55,481
We're having a little tiny vard problem.

72
00:02:55,721 --> 00:02:59,081
Me and my vardies have just pollinated
three miles of wheat.

73
00:02:59,321 --> 00:03:00,921
GOODTHING: You've got to keep smiling.

74
00:03:01,001 --> 00:03:02,281
KEZZIA: Got to what?

75
00:03:02,481 --> 00:03:03,481
It's the vardies.

76
00:03:03,561 --> 00:03:05,241
God, what's wrong with you?

77
00:03:05,361 --> 00:03:07,321
Is that smile supposed to look real?

78
00:03:07,401 --> 00:03:09,201
It's like you're standing
in a wind tunnel.

79
00:03:10,001 --> 00:03:12,241
Hey, big smiles now.

80
00:03:12,321 --> 00:03:14,041
Brace yourself.

81
00:03:14,121 --> 00:03:15,601
Mum is dead.

82
00:03:16,001 --> 00:03:17,121
Sorry?

83
00:03:17,201 --> 00:03:18,201
Smile, smile, smile.

84
00:03:18,401 --> 00:03:19,761
That's not even funny.

85
00:03:19,841 --> 00:03:20,881
No, it's not a joke.

86
00:03:21,241 --> 00:03:24,481
Mum is dead. Mum is dead.

87
00:03:25,161 --> 00:03:27,281
And Hopeful, she's dead, too.

88
00:03:27,521 --> 00:03:29,841
And her friend, Sunshine, she's dead.

89
00:03:29,921 --> 00:03:31,161
And Eliza

90
00:03:31,241 --> 00:03:33,561
and quite a few other people are dead.

91
00:03:33,641 --> 00:03:35,041
KEZZIA: Why are you saying this?

92
00:03:35,601 --> 00:03:39,001
You can't say things like that
grinning like an idiot.

93
00:03:39,281 --> 00:03:42,521
GOODTHING: Smile, really. Try.
If you don't... (PANTING)

94
00:03:43,041 --> 00:03:45,161
I shouldn't have told you. Please smile.

95
00:03:45,401 --> 00:03:46,401
(BEEPS)

96
00:03:46,761 --> 00:03:48,961
(FAKE LAUGHTER) You're on two tears now.

97
00:03:49,721 --> 00:03:51,281
KEZZIA: Is it hugging me?

98
00:03:51,361 --> 00:03:52,801
(VARDIES DRILLING)

99
00:03:53,081 --> 00:03:54,601
Who programmed that?

100
00:03:54,841 --> 00:03:56,841
GOODTHING: Please, give her a moment.

101
00:03:57,561 --> 00:03:59,561
She'll be happy in a moment. (CHUCKLES)

102
00:03:59,961 --> 00:04:01,641
-Kezzia!
-(KEZZIA SCREAMING)

103
00:04:06,681 --> 00:04:08,001
No, look.

104
00:04:08,201 --> 00:04:09,641
(SHUDDERING) I'm smiling.

105
00:04:10,641 --> 00:04:12,161
(GASPS) Smiling!

106
00:04:12,681 --> 00:04:14,281
(GOODTHING SCREAMING)

107
00:04:16,401 --> 00:04:18,401
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

108
00:04:53,921 --> 00:04:55,121
BILL: Which way is Earth?

109
00:04:55,241 --> 00:04:56,801
DOCTOR: Ah, space is bent.

110
00:04:57,641 --> 00:05:00,001
Earth is any way you choose to look.

111
00:05:00,761 --> 00:05:01,881
Why? You're thinking about leaving?

112
00:05:02,601 --> 00:05:05,001
Thinking? I'm not thinking.
My brain's overloading.

113
00:05:06,281 --> 00:05:08,361
-Why a phone box?
-DOCTOR: I told you.

114
00:05:09,361 --> 00:05:11,681
BILL: Yeah, well,
I get it's a cloaking device.

115
00:05:12,041 --> 00:05:14,401
But why keep it that shape?
Why do you like it?

116
00:05:14,521 --> 00:05:15,921
DOCTOR: Who said I like it?

117
00:05:16,001 --> 00:05:17,961
BILL: You kept it.
DOCTOR: Come along.

118
00:05:20,801 --> 00:05:22,521
This is one
of the Earth's first colonies.

119
00:05:22,721 --> 00:05:24,881
They say the settlers have cracked

120
00:05:24,961 --> 00:05:27,121
the secret of human happiness.

121
00:05:27,601 --> 00:05:28,601
(CAMERA CLICKS)

122
00:05:29,961 --> 00:05:31,081
BILL: One question.

123
00:05:31,641 --> 00:05:32,961
Little fella said you made an oath?

124
00:05:33,521 --> 00:05:35,041
You're not supposed to leave the planet.

125
00:05:36,201 --> 00:05:39,001
DOCTOR: Okay, I suppose
I owe you an explanation.

126
00:05:39,481 --> 00:05:40,681
(CLEARS THROAT)

127
00:05:41,841 --> 00:05:43,841
A long time ago, a thing happened.

128
00:05:43,921 --> 00:05:45,281
As a result of the thing,

129
00:05:45,641 --> 00:05:48,001
I made a promise.
As a result of the promise,

130
00:05:48,081 --> 00:05:49,201
I have to stay on Earth.

131
00:05:49,561 --> 00:05:50,561
Guarding a vault?

132
00:05:50,681 --> 00:05:51,881
Guarding a vault.

133
00:05:53,641 --> 00:05:55,081
BILL: Well, you're not guarding
the vault right now.

134
00:05:55,241 --> 00:05:58,321
Yes, I am. I have a time machine.
I can be back before we left.

135
00:05:59,321 --> 00:06:01,601
But what if you get lost,
or stuck or something?

136
00:06:01,681 --> 00:06:03,321
I've thought about that.

137
00:06:03,401 --> 00:06:04,401
And?

138
00:06:04,481 --> 00:06:06,521
Well, it would be a worry,
so best not to dwell on it.

139
00:06:06,601 --> 00:06:08,401
Look at this building, look at it.

140
00:06:08,881 --> 00:06:10,961
You know what I really like
about humanity?

141
00:06:11,681 --> 00:06:12,961
-It's optimism.
-(BUZZING)

142
00:06:13,081 --> 00:06:14,601
Do you know
what this building is made of?

143
00:06:14,681 --> 00:06:17,521
Pure, soaring optimism.

144
00:06:23,321 --> 00:06:24,641
What're they?

145
00:06:24,761 --> 00:06:26,121
Alien birds?

146
00:06:28,401 --> 00:06:29,441
Vardies.

147
00:06:30,121 --> 00:06:31,241
Tiny robots.

148
00:06:32,441 --> 00:06:36,481
Work in flocks.
They're versatile, hardworking.

149
00:06:38,361 --> 00:06:40,121
Good at learning skills.

150
00:06:40,881 --> 00:06:42,881
The worker bees
of the third industrial revolution.

151
00:06:43,281 --> 00:06:45,561
Probably just checking us out
for security.

152
00:06:45,641 --> 00:06:48,401
These are robots?
These are disappointing robots.

153
00:06:50,521 --> 00:06:51,881
That's a very offensive remark.

154
00:06:52,081 --> 00:06:53,841
Don't make personal remarks like that.

155
00:06:54,681 --> 00:06:56,121
Er, you can't offend the machine.

156
00:06:56,281 --> 00:06:58,001
DOCTOR: Typical, wet-brained
chauvinism.

157
00:06:58,681 --> 00:07:00,361
-(BEEPING, STATIC)
-Oh, what just happened?

158
00:07:01,441 --> 00:07:02,561
DOCTOR: Your ear's on fire.

159
00:07:02,641 --> 00:07:04,841
Argh, your voice just came out
in my ear.

160
00:07:05,161 --> 00:07:08,201
I mean, I know voices go into ears,
but this is like...

161
00:07:08,401 --> 00:07:10,521
We have been fitted
with some kind of communication device.

162
00:07:10,601 --> 00:07:13,281
It is using our own nervous system
as hardware.

163
00:07:13,481 --> 00:07:15,721
We've just downloaded an upgrade
for our ears.

164
00:07:15,801 --> 00:07:17,081
BILL: I'll never lose my phone again.

165
00:07:17,161 --> 00:07:19,201
I'll never run out of battery again!

166
00:07:19,361 --> 00:07:20,761
Welcome to paradise.

167
00:07:20,841 --> 00:07:23,401
Hang on, is there a mute button though?
Like, what if we're in the loo?

168
00:07:23,521 --> 00:07:26,081
Who needs loos?
There's probably an app for that.

169
00:07:28,161 --> 00:07:29,521
So, where is everyone?

170
00:07:30,481 --> 00:07:32,121
Don't tell me
we've come halfway across the universe

171
00:07:32,201 --> 00:07:33,521
and they've all gone out.

172
00:07:33,921 --> 00:07:35,121
Should have texted first or something.

173
00:07:35,201 --> 00:07:36,521
-(WHIRRING)
-(GASPS)

174
00:07:41,081 --> 00:07:42,201
BILL: What's that?

175
00:07:43,721 --> 00:07:45,681
That is a robot.

176
00:07:45,921 --> 00:07:48,481
That is not a disappointing robot.

177
00:07:49,321 --> 00:07:51,161
DOCTOR: Technically,
this isn't a robot at all.

178
00:07:52,081 --> 00:07:54,281
The tiny little things,
those are the robots.

179
00:07:54,401 --> 00:07:56,121
This is the interface for them.

180
00:07:56,201 --> 00:07:57,321
Does it speak?

181
00:07:58,241 --> 00:07:59,281
Will we understand it?

182
00:07:59,441 --> 00:08:01,921
DOCTOR: Well, depends upon
what aspect of your language

183
00:08:02,001 --> 00:08:03,961
has survived
over so many thousands of years.

184
00:08:05,161 --> 00:08:07,081
Emoji! It speaks emoji!

185
00:08:07,441 --> 00:08:08,481
Of course, it does.

186
00:08:09,521 --> 00:08:11,161
Aw, it's cute.

187
00:08:16,161 --> 00:08:17,241
BILL: What's that?

188
00:08:17,321 --> 00:08:18,441
DOCTOR: Blank patches.

189
00:08:21,641 --> 00:08:23,921
BILL: Oh, yours isn't blank.
It's got a face on the back.

190
00:08:24,241 --> 00:08:25,641
DOCTOR: Yours too.

191
00:08:28,721 --> 00:08:29,801
Interesting.

192
00:08:30,161 --> 00:08:32,321
BILL: It's never on the side
that you're looking at.

193
00:08:33,881 --> 00:08:36,321
What's it doing now? What...
What face is it making?

194
00:08:36,401 --> 00:08:38,001
Mmm, sort of puzzled. Me?

195
00:08:38,841 --> 00:08:40,601
-Same.
-Hmm.

196
00:08:41,321 --> 00:08:42,601
DOCTOR: Do you know what I think?

197
00:08:42,681 --> 00:08:46,001
I think that this is some kind
of a mood indicator.

198
00:08:46,121 --> 00:08:48,121
BILL: But you're never allowed
to see your own mood?

199
00:08:48,481 --> 00:08:50,001
-Makes sense.
-Does it?

200
00:08:50,081 --> 00:08:52,881
Well, seeing your own mood
might affect your own mood.

201
00:08:52,961 --> 00:08:54,521
It's like a feedback loop,

202
00:08:54,961 --> 00:08:57,481
interfering with
the information being collected.

203
00:08:57,921 --> 00:08:59,841
Like a scale weighing itself.

204
00:09:00,441 --> 00:09:01,961
Well, who's collecting the data?

205
00:09:02,561 --> 00:09:03,721
It's the big question.

206
00:09:03,801 --> 00:09:05,001
BILL: So, what do we do, then?

207
00:09:05,081 --> 00:09:06,881
Well, if they're badges, then...

208
00:09:07,881 --> 00:09:08,921
(BEEPS)

209
00:09:09,401 --> 00:09:10,641
What? Where's...

210
00:09:10,721 --> 00:09:12,361
-Where's it gone?
-BILL: Oh, it's on your back.

211
00:09:15,521 --> 00:09:16,561
DOCTOR: Oh, yours too.

212
00:09:18,601 --> 00:09:20,961
So, everyone you walk past
can see what you're thinking.

213
00:09:21,081 --> 00:09:22,681
What if you really fancy someone?

214
00:09:23,081 --> 00:09:26,081
Well, I suppose it means that you have
to maintain eye contact with them.

215
00:09:26,241 --> 00:09:27,721
Oh, that's brilliant.

216
00:09:29,361 --> 00:09:30,881
DOCTOR: Welcome to the future.

217
00:09:35,961 --> 00:09:38,401
Emojis, verbal communications.

218
00:09:38,481 --> 00:09:40,801
We're in the utopia of vacuous teens.

219
00:09:42,441 --> 00:09:44,401
(EMOJIBOT ARMS WHIRRING)

220
00:09:47,921 --> 00:09:49,441
BILL: Look at this!

221
00:09:49,521 --> 00:09:51,001
It knew I was starving.

222
00:09:51,121 --> 00:09:53,241
Food from another planet.

223
00:09:53,681 --> 00:09:55,361
What? You gotta have it in.

224
00:09:56,441 --> 00:09:58,161
(SNIFFS) Smells like fish.

225
00:09:58,641 --> 00:10:00,041
I'm not that fond of fish.

226
00:10:00,761 --> 00:10:03,241
Except socially,
which can complicate a meal like this.

227
00:10:04,521 --> 00:10:05,801
Should we eat though?

228
00:10:05,881 --> 00:10:07,481
I mean, what if they're not like us?

229
00:10:07,561 --> 00:10:08,841
Well, the cutlery is human cutlery.

230
00:10:09,081 --> 00:10:11,201
No other species
in the universe uses emojis.

231
00:10:11,361 --> 00:10:12,641
Everything here is human.

232
00:10:13,001 --> 00:10:14,081
Except...

233
00:10:15,561 --> 00:10:16,721
No humans.

234
00:10:16,801 --> 00:10:19,001
This is a perfect colony for humans, so,

235
00:10:19,121 --> 00:10:20,761
where are all the colonists?

236
00:10:21,601 --> 00:10:25,281
That's some sort of flavoured algae.

237
00:10:26,161 --> 00:10:28,081
I haven't seen any livestock yet.

238
00:10:28,161 --> 00:10:29,761
BILL: That's good, isn't it?

239
00:10:30,721 --> 00:10:33,481
In the future, we don't eat
living things, we eat algae.

240
00:10:33,601 --> 00:10:35,841
I met an emperor made of algae once.

241
00:10:38,561 --> 00:10:39,721
He fancied me.

242
00:10:44,201 --> 00:10:45,601
Why aren't you loving this?

243
00:10:45,681 --> 00:10:47,001
Everything is here.

244
00:10:47,521 --> 00:10:49,681
Everything is ready,
but there's no one here.

245
00:10:50,041 --> 00:10:51,401
It's like the student union
first thing,

246
00:10:51,481 --> 00:10:52,841
before the actual students arrive.

247
00:10:53,401 --> 00:10:54,601
Two portions though.

248
00:10:55,121 --> 00:10:57,041
DOCTOR: Well,
that's because that one is mine.

249
00:11:00,641 --> 00:11:01,641
That's it.

250
00:11:02,841 --> 00:11:04,281
That it! Of course!

251
00:11:04,681 --> 00:11:06,401
The whole place is waiting.

252
00:11:07,241 --> 00:11:08,361
We're just too early.

253
00:11:08,441 --> 00:11:09,601
BILL: So, who's still in bed?

254
00:11:10,401 --> 00:11:12,281
Two portions. One portion.

255
00:11:12,561 --> 00:11:14,761
Is there going to be food sexism
even in the future?

256
00:11:15,161 --> 00:11:16,441
Is this bloke utopia?

257
00:11:16,561 --> 00:11:19,321
It's probably reading me as two people.
The heartbeats.

258
00:11:19,401 --> 00:11:21,521
If you're going to travel
20 light years,

259
00:11:21,601 --> 00:11:22,841
you're going to want to make sure

260
00:11:22,921 --> 00:11:25,121
that you've got somewhere
to sleep at the end of it, aren't you?

261
00:11:25,201 --> 00:11:26,361
So, what do you do?

262
00:11:26,441 --> 00:11:28,161
Sorry. Two hearts?

263
00:11:28,241 --> 00:11:31,641
You send a rocket load
of intelligent robots up ahead of you.

264
00:11:31,721 --> 00:11:33,801
They build you a place to live,

265
00:11:33,881 --> 00:11:36,081
so that when you arrive,
it's all waiting.

266
00:11:36,201 --> 00:11:37,361
This is brilliant!

267
00:11:37,641 --> 00:11:39,801
(STUTTERING) You've got two hearts.

268
00:11:39,881 --> 00:11:41,481
Robots, they don't breathe.

269
00:11:41,561 --> 00:11:44,361
They can fix the atmosphere for you,
send data back.

270
00:11:44,881 --> 00:11:47,121
So, you know whether
to bring your waterproofs or not.

271
00:11:47,601 --> 00:11:51,401
Working, huge robot flocks.

272
00:11:51,601 --> 00:11:55,041
You just send them up ahead
and you leave them to it.

273
00:11:55,161 --> 00:11:56,441
Yeah, hearts though, why two?

274
00:11:56,641 --> 00:11:57,641
Oh, why one?

275
00:11:59,321 --> 00:12:01,521
Does that mean
you've got really high blood pressure?

276
00:12:02,761 --> 00:12:03,961
Really high.

277
00:12:10,641 --> 00:12:13,801
BILL: So, since people aren't here yet.
What do we do?

278
00:12:15,161 --> 00:12:16,401
Put a kettle on?

279
00:12:17,881 --> 00:12:19,961
Or are we going to leave
before they arrive?

280
00:12:21,401 --> 00:12:22,961
Is that what you're worried about?

281
00:12:26,521 --> 00:12:27,881
I can see you're worried.

282
00:12:28,441 --> 00:12:30,921
DOCTOR: Well, you never know
what's around the next corner.

283
00:12:36,041 --> 00:12:37,961
Ah, of course.

284
00:12:38,041 --> 00:12:39,441
Wheat fields outside,

285
00:12:39,521 --> 00:12:41,881
now there's something else to eat
when they get here.

286
00:12:42,441 --> 00:12:44,841
This is their crops.

287
00:12:46,201 --> 00:12:49,521
Look, they're going to have orchards,
olive groves.

288
00:12:49,601 --> 00:12:50,681
This is their nursery.

289
00:12:50,761 --> 00:12:53,401
Look, little robots
are doing pollination work.

290
00:12:53,641 --> 00:12:54,721
Oh, this plant!

291
00:12:54,921 --> 00:12:56,681
There's one of these growing outside
the student union.

292
00:12:56,761 --> 00:12:58,081
It smells amazing.

293
00:13:01,161 --> 00:13:02,201
DOCTOR: Rosemary.

294
00:13:02,281 --> 00:13:04,041
I'm smelling home.

295
00:13:04,121 --> 00:13:06,001
Twenty light years from home.

296
00:13:07,241 --> 00:13:08,481
(GIGGLES)

297
00:13:08,841 --> 00:13:10,201
Thanks for bringing me.

298
00:13:11,281 --> 00:13:12,881
This is a great day out.

299
00:13:14,041 --> 00:13:15,641
I mean, come on,

300
00:13:15,721 --> 00:13:17,201
admit it, you love it.

301
00:13:17,801 --> 00:13:18,921
Did I say I didn't love it?

302
00:13:19,001 --> 00:13:21,641
Yes, I do, it's very... Lovable.

303
00:13:22,281 --> 00:13:23,761
You asked me where all the people were.

304
00:13:23,841 --> 00:13:27,121
I theorised that
they hadn't got here yet.

305
00:13:27,201 --> 00:13:28,761
Did I sound convincing?

306
00:13:29,801 --> 00:13:32,241
-Yeah.
-And did I convince myself?

307
00:13:33,561 --> 00:13:34,961
BILL: No.
DOCTOR: No.

308
00:13:35,241 --> 00:13:37,521
No, and I'll tell you why,
because there should be somebody here.

309
00:13:38,801 --> 00:13:41,641
There should be some kind of a...
A set up team.

310
00:13:42,041 --> 00:13:43,641
A skeleton crew.

311
00:13:45,321 --> 00:13:46,441
You're thinking.

312
00:13:47,161 --> 00:13:48,401
Tell me what you're thinking about.

313
00:13:48,881 --> 00:13:50,041
A magic haddock.

314
00:13:50,881 --> 00:13:51,881
Obviously.

315
00:13:56,041 --> 00:13:57,801
What is this stuff? Is it snow?

316
00:14:00,361 --> 00:14:02,001
This is fertiliser.

317
00:14:02,801 --> 00:14:04,081
Mineral fertiliser.

318
00:14:05,081 --> 00:14:06,801
Calcium based. Now.

319
00:14:07,281 --> 00:14:09,641
We don't have answers,
so let's put together two questions.

320
00:14:09,721 --> 00:14:12,001
What is the source of this
mineral fertiliser?

321
00:14:12,081 --> 00:14:13,081
(HISSING)

322
00:14:15,641 --> 00:14:16,761
Where are all the people?

323
00:14:22,481 --> 00:14:23,761
Ugh! (GASPS)

324
00:14:24,761 --> 00:14:25,881
Here.

325
00:14:26,681 --> 00:14:27,721
Right here.

326
00:14:28,001 --> 00:14:29,201
In this garden.

327
00:14:29,441 --> 00:14:30,721
Oh, my God.

328
00:14:37,841 --> 00:14:39,321
(SCREAMING)

329
00:14:46,761 --> 00:14:49,161
DOCTOR: Despite appearances,
they haven't been dead very long.

330
00:14:50,721 --> 00:14:52,001
What? Those are the colonists?

331
00:14:52,841 --> 00:14:54,241
The colonists aren't here yet.

332
00:14:54,641 --> 00:14:55,761
This is the set up team.

333
00:14:56,441 --> 00:14:57,561
The skeleton crew.

334
00:14:57,641 --> 00:14:59,361
Well, why did the robots feed them
to the garden?

335
00:14:59,441 --> 00:15:01,201
DOCTOR: I don't know.
Maybe they ran out of fertiliser.

336
00:15:01,281 --> 00:15:02,361
Let's not ask them.

337
00:15:03,361 --> 00:15:04,961
(MECHANICAL WARBLING)

338
00:15:05,041 --> 00:15:07,081
-DOCTOR: Hello.
-(STAMMERS)

339
00:15:07,161 --> 00:15:09,321
-Er, we were just admiring your garden.
-Yes!

340
00:15:09,401 --> 00:15:12,841
We'll be gone now because there's
nothing of particular interest here.

341
00:15:12,921 --> 00:15:13,921
Cheerio!

342
00:15:19,841 --> 00:15:21,841
If he's chasing us,
he's moving very slowly.

343
00:15:21,921 --> 00:15:23,961
Do you know what it means
if something chases you very slowly?

344
00:15:24,041 --> 00:15:25,161
-What?
-It means,

345
00:15:25,241 --> 00:15:27,081
there's a reason
that they don't have to run.

346
00:15:32,481 --> 00:15:33,481
(GASPS)

347
00:15:36,361 --> 00:15:37,841
Okay, they're slow
but the city's full of 'em.

348
00:15:37,921 --> 00:15:38,921
So they catch you in the end.

349
00:15:39,001 --> 00:15:40,281
And what do we do?

350
00:15:40,361 --> 00:15:42,641
The question. We've been here for ages.

351
00:15:42,721 --> 00:15:43,921
Why are they taking us now?

352
00:15:44,001 --> 00:15:45,081
Does it matter?

353
00:15:45,161 --> 00:15:46,241
Only if we want to live.

354
00:15:48,601 --> 00:15:49,641
Smile for me.

355
00:15:49,761 --> 00:15:50,761
Smile?

356
00:15:51,761 --> 00:15:53,761
Use your whole face. Right now. Do it.

357
00:15:54,721 --> 00:15:56,201
Er, what good's smiling?

358
00:15:56,321 --> 00:15:57,881
Smiles aren't just smiles.

359
00:15:58,121 --> 00:16:01,401
Psychologically, they have
a measurable effect on your mood states.

360
00:16:01,921 --> 00:16:03,001
Yes!

361
00:16:04,241 --> 00:16:07,601
These robots, they built this place,
they grew those trees.

362
00:16:08,121 --> 00:16:10,721
Something went wrong, but they were
designed to make you happy.

363
00:16:10,841 --> 00:16:13,361
How would massacring hundreds of people
make me happy?

364
00:16:13,481 --> 00:16:16,761
"How would massacring hundreds of people
make me happy?” Smiley face.

365
00:16:18,321 --> 00:16:19,321
Smiley face.

366
00:16:19,521 --> 00:16:20,601
Magic haddock.

367
00:16:20,761 --> 00:16:22,961
What magic haddock?
What's that all about?

368
00:16:23,241 --> 00:16:25,761
The robots want you to be happy
but they got the wrong end of the stick.

369
00:16:25,841 --> 00:16:28,641
I think we should give them
what they want.

370
00:16:30,041 --> 00:16:31,081
(SIGHS)

371
00:16:36,161 --> 00:16:38,921
Don't even try without smiling.

372
00:16:39,481 --> 00:16:42,921
What a lovely place you have here!

373
00:16:43,001 --> 00:16:45,321
Thank you so much for your hospitality.

374
00:16:45,561 --> 00:16:48,081
We will come again. (CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY)

375
00:16:49,041 --> 00:16:53,161
Doctor, I... I was thinking, maybe
next time we might go to Wiltshire,

376
00:16:53,241 --> 00:16:54,361
perhaps. (CHUCKLES)

377
00:16:54,441 --> 00:16:55,801
Or Aberdeen.

378
00:16:56,361 --> 00:17:03,161
Ah, yes. Two thumbs up
for Wiltshire/Aberdeen.

379
00:17:12,361 --> 00:17:13,401
(GASPS)

380
00:17:13,521 --> 00:17:15,281
-Doctor!
-Smile!

381
00:17:15,361 --> 00:17:17,041
-Smile!
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

382
00:17:18,161 --> 00:17:19,281
(GASPING)

383
00:17:20,441 --> 00:17:22,241
(BUZZING)

384
00:17:22,321 --> 00:17:23,681
BILL: Where did they come from?

385
00:17:23,761 --> 00:17:26,121
DOCTOR: Once we're out of the city,
we should be safe.

386
00:17:40,321 --> 00:17:41,601
BILL: Are they coming after us?

387
00:17:42,401 --> 00:17:45,401
I'm guessing that once we're out,
we're not their problem.

388
00:17:45,561 --> 00:17:47,001
(PANTING)

389
00:17:47,561 --> 00:17:49,841
Right. You'll be perfectly safe
in the TARDIS.

390
00:17:49,921 --> 00:17:51,641
She'll look after you till I get back.

391
00:17:51,721 --> 00:17:52,761
Where are you going?

392
00:17:56,321 --> 00:17:58,761
There's a giant smiley abattoir
over there.

393
00:17:58,841 --> 00:18:01,201
And I'm having this
really childish impulse to blow it up!

394
00:18:01,281 --> 00:18:02,361
Be right back.

395
00:18:02,441 --> 00:18:04,401
What, you're going back in?
We've only just escaped.

396
00:18:04,681 --> 00:18:05,961
I thought we were going home.

397
00:18:07,961 --> 00:18:08,961
Home?

398
00:18:10,641 --> 00:18:12,241
Why would we be going home?

399
00:18:12,321 --> 00:18:14,241
That place is a living death trap.

400
00:18:14,321 --> 00:18:15,841
We can't just leave it
with its mouth wide open.

401
00:18:15,921 --> 00:18:17,401
But they're all dead.

402
00:18:17,481 --> 00:18:18,961
We saw them, it's too late.

403
00:18:19,041 --> 00:18:21,921
We have to assume
that there is a colony ship on the way.

404
00:18:22,001 --> 00:18:24,081
What do you think is gonna happen
when all those people arrive?

405
00:18:24,281 --> 00:18:26,161
They're expecting
the new Garden of Eden.

406
00:18:26,241 --> 00:18:28,881
What they are not expecting
is to be the fertiliser.

407
00:18:30,081 --> 00:18:32,921
There's broadband in there.
Go and watch some movies or something.

408
00:18:33,121 --> 00:18:34,641
Well, I get that
someone has to do something,

409
00:18:34,721 --> 00:18:35,921
but why is it you?

410
00:18:36,401 --> 00:18:37,881
Can't you phone the police?

411
00:18:38,481 --> 00:18:40,201
Isn't there a helpline or something?

412
00:18:41,081 --> 00:18:43,481
And stay away from my browser history!

413
00:18:44,521 --> 00:18:45,561
(SIGHS)

414
00:18:57,361 --> 00:18:59,121
A penguin with his arse on fire.

415
00:19:17,961 --> 00:19:18,961
Huh.

416
00:19:24,401 --> 00:19:26,041
(BEEPING)

417
00:19:29,961 --> 00:19:30,961
Ah.

418
00:19:31,961 --> 00:19:33,201
-(BEEPS)
-Good morning.

419
00:19:34,001 --> 00:19:35,041
I'm happy.

420
00:19:35,961 --> 00:19:39,321
Good morning. Look at me. I'm...
I'm happy, happy, happy, happy...

421
00:19:39,521 --> 00:19:42,561
What a lovely, beautiful morning.
It makes me so happy.

422
00:19:43,161 --> 00:19:45,161
I'm happy,
I hope that you are happy too.

423
00:19:48,641 --> 00:19:49,641
See?

424
00:19:50,121 --> 00:19:51,201
Happy.

425
00:19:52,001 --> 00:19:53,401
(BEEPS)

426
00:20:09,201 --> 00:20:10,281
(STAMP BEEPS)

427
00:20:13,641 --> 00:20:15,721
-(BEEPS)
-Hello, is someone there?

428
00:20:16,681 --> 00:20:17,761
I can hear you breathing.

429
00:20:18,281 --> 00:20:19,401
Why are you Scottish?

430
00:20:21,081 --> 00:20:22,961
I'm not Scottish. I'm just cross.

431
00:20:23,041 --> 00:20:24,441
BILL: Is there a Scotland in space?

432
00:20:24,561 --> 00:20:25,521
They are all over the place.

433
00:20:25,641 --> 00:20:27,441
Demanding independence from every planet
that they land on.

434
00:20:27,521 --> 00:20:28,601
Why are you here?

435
00:20:28,681 --> 00:20:31,161
Because I figured out why you keep
your box as a phone box.

436
00:20:31,241 --> 00:20:32,321
I told you, it's stuck.

437
00:20:32,401 --> 00:20:34,921
"Advice and assistance
obtainable immediately."

438
00:20:35,041 --> 00:20:36,521
-You like that.
-No, I don't.

439
00:20:36,681 --> 00:20:38,321
See, this is the point.

440
00:20:38,601 --> 00:20:42,801
You don't call the helpline
because you are the helpline.

441
00:20:42,921 --> 00:20:44,121
Don't sentimentalise me.

442
00:20:44,201 --> 00:20:46,241
I don't just fly around
helping people out.

443
00:20:46,601 --> 00:20:47,681
What are you doing right now?

444
00:20:48,561 --> 00:20:51,121
I happened to be passing by
so I'm mucking in.

445
00:20:51,281 --> 00:20:52,721
You never passed by in your life.

446
00:20:53,281 --> 00:20:54,841
You couldn't even leave me
serving chips.

447
00:20:54,921 --> 00:20:56,441
So, I'm not gonna leave you.

448
00:20:57,921 --> 00:20:59,001
Look at the wall.

449
00:21:00,281 --> 00:21:01,441
-The wall?
-Closely.

450
00:21:06,041 --> 00:21:09,761
Before, when the vardi, the little
microbots, were going to attack you,

451
00:21:10,081 --> 00:21:11,521
you asked me where they came from.

452
00:21:13,841 --> 00:21:14,961
Well, they didn't come from anywhere.

453
00:21:16,601 --> 00:21:18,161
They were here all the time.

454
00:21:18,961 --> 00:21:20,841
BILL: (STUTTERS) In the wall?

455
00:21:21,641 --> 00:21:23,601
DOCTOR: No. Not in the wall.

456
00:21:28,201 --> 00:21:30,921
They're not in the wall.
They are the wall.

457
00:21:31,001 --> 00:21:32,521
-They're all the walls.
-(BUZZING)

458
00:21:32,721 --> 00:21:35,321
These little robots
didn't build this place.

459
00:21:35,401 --> 00:21:36,441
They became it.

460
00:21:36,521 --> 00:21:39,001
They can be a part of a wall
one minute, flying around the next.

461
00:21:39,081 --> 00:21:43,881
This whole structure is built
from interlocking microbots.

462
00:21:44,201 --> 00:21:45,641
(BUZZING STOPS)

463
00:21:47,881 --> 00:21:50,681
Smile. You're in the belly of the beast.

464
00:21:52,161 --> 00:21:53,361
So what do we do?

465
00:21:53,561 --> 00:21:55,401
Well, the obvious. We find a real wall.

466
00:21:57,001 --> 00:21:58,481
Oh, you really are smiling, aren't you?

467
00:21:58,601 --> 00:21:59,961
(CHUCKLES) Do you know why?

468
00:22:01,001 --> 00:22:03,041
You're an awesome tutor.

469
00:22:05,761 --> 00:22:09,441
When the Vikings invaded, they used to
pull the longboats out of the water,

470
00:22:09,521 --> 00:22:10,601
turn them upside down

471
00:22:11,081 --> 00:22:12,481
and live in them as houses

472
00:22:12,561 --> 00:22:15,201
until they pillaged and looted enough
to build new ones.

473
00:22:16,441 --> 00:22:17,521
So?

474
00:22:17,601 --> 00:22:19,441
You didn't see
a spaceship outside, did you?

475
00:22:20,001 --> 00:22:22,041
When the settlers first landed,
they must have lived in it

476
00:22:22,121 --> 00:22:24,081
and built out from it,

477
00:22:24,921 --> 00:22:26,041
so it's still here.

478
00:22:26,881 --> 00:22:28,481
Somewhere inside this building.

479
00:22:31,161 --> 00:22:32,601
Ah...

480
00:22:34,881 --> 00:22:36,201
Bits of meteor damage.

481
00:22:36,481 --> 00:22:38,681
Flakes of rust. Rivets.
Oh, I love rivets.

482
00:22:38,761 --> 00:22:43,281
A wall. A real, honest wall. Not made of
tiny robots but made of any old iron.

483
00:22:43,361 --> 00:22:46,841
Every spacecraft needs... A door!

484
00:22:48,801 --> 00:22:49,801
(GRUNTING)

485
00:22:54,041 --> 00:22:55,041
(BEEPS)

486
00:22:56,161 --> 00:22:57,201
Not even locked.

487
00:22:58,041 --> 00:22:59,761
(DOOR WHOOSHING)

488
00:23:03,321 --> 00:23:05,081
They were expecting to live in peace.

489
00:23:11,761 --> 00:23:12,761
Wicked.

490
00:23:12,921 --> 00:23:14,641
We'll lock it after us, shall we?

491
00:23:20,441 --> 00:23:21,721
(POWERING UP)

492
00:23:25,561 --> 00:23:27,601
(ENGINES HUMMING)

493
00:23:30,281 --> 00:23:31,921
It's life support systems
are starting up.

494
00:23:32,001 --> 00:23:33,281
It knows we're here.

495
00:23:34,521 --> 00:23:36,121
Whoever did
the interior decoration in here

496
00:23:36,201 --> 00:23:38,201
needs to take lessons
from whoever did the out there.

497
00:23:38,281 --> 00:23:41,481
Ah. This was built by humans.
That was built by vardi.

498
00:23:41,561 --> 00:23:43,361
Wet brains, dry brains.

499
00:23:55,921 --> 00:23:56,921
Ah...

500
00:23:57,841 --> 00:23:58,921
(CHUCKLES)

501
00:24:00,961 --> 00:24:04,441
Good old, universally-compatible

502
00:24:04,521 --> 00:24:08,321
incorruptible maps.

503
00:24:10,321 --> 00:24:11,401
You are here.

504
00:24:13,401 --> 00:24:14,681
This is the engine room.

505
00:24:15,121 --> 00:24:17,401
That's the target.
That's where I'm going.

506
00:24:17,601 --> 00:24:19,321
-Where am I going?
-You are staying here.

507
00:24:20,241 --> 00:24:23,841
And you will be guiding me to here
using this map.

508
00:24:24,601 --> 00:24:27,841
I'll hear you through the thingamabob.

509
00:24:28,961 --> 00:24:30,281
BILL: I'm on a spaceship.

510
00:24:31,161 --> 00:24:32,321
Like, for real.

511
00:24:33,841 --> 00:24:34,881
A proper one.

512
00:24:36,321 --> 00:24:38,801
-DOCTOR: Left or right?
-Oh! Er...

513
00:24:41,281 --> 00:24:42,281
Right.

514
00:24:42,681 --> 00:24:46,161
Well, they were certainly planning
to make themselves at home here.

515
00:24:47,241 --> 00:24:49,801
They brought
all their favourite knick-knacks.

516
00:24:50,041 --> 00:24:53,561
Er, there should be a door
that leads on to a corridor.

517
00:24:55,081 --> 00:24:58,241
-(CHUCKLES) I really am on a spaceship.
-DOCTOR: Yes...

518
00:24:58,761 --> 00:25:00,921
Which we are about to blow up.

519
00:25:01,041 --> 00:25:02,161
How are you allowed to do that?

520
00:25:02,921 --> 00:25:06,561
Like, how are you allowed to blow
something up and not get into trouble.

521
00:25:06,641 --> 00:25:08,801
I mean, blow something up,
get into trouble.

522
00:25:08,881 --> 00:25:11,281
That is a standard sequence.

523
00:25:11,601 --> 00:25:14,481
What do you mean "allowed"?
It's a moral imperative.

524
00:25:14,761 --> 00:25:16,201
This is a murder machine.

525
00:25:16,801 --> 00:25:19,361
Beautiful though.
I mean, the whole place.

526
00:25:20,361 --> 00:25:23,161
Er, you should be able
to see a staircase.

527
00:25:23,441 --> 00:25:25,521
All traps are beautiful.
That's how they work.

528
00:25:26,001 --> 00:25:27,761
-Up or down?
-Down.

529
00:25:30,601 --> 00:25:32,761
What... What's this big bit
in the middle?

530
00:25:33,361 --> 00:25:35,361
There's a big, empty space
in the middle.

531
00:25:35,961 --> 00:25:39,041
The engine is in the middle
of a big, empty space.

532
00:25:39,481 --> 00:25:40,481
What's that for?

533
00:25:40,641 --> 00:25:41,761
-WOMAN: (ON PA) Attention.
-(GASPS)

534
00:25:41,881 --> 00:25:45,121
Attention. Error one systems initiated.

535
00:25:45,201 --> 00:25:47,961
Ship's system's set to respond
to human presence.

536
00:25:48,041 --> 00:25:51,561
It was sleeping. We walked in.
Now it's waking up.

537
00:25:51,841 --> 00:25:55,081
-Er, there should be a ladder.
-Got it.

538
00:25:58,721 --> 00:26:00,361
(GRUNTING)

539
00:26:07,121 --> 00:26:09,001
-(AIR HISSING)
-(ALARM BLARING)

540
00:26:18,201 --> 00:26:19,201
Pitiful.

541
00:26:19,321 --> 00:26:20,961
Fleischman cold fusion engine.

542
00:26:21,041 --> 00:26:24,761
AW I got to do is back the flow
into the calorimeter and run.

543
00:26:24,961 --> 00:26:27,001
(CHUCKLES) It's like
it wants to get blown up.

544
00:26:30,881 --> 00:26:34,001
Hang on, I'm being thick.
I can come with you.

545
00:26:34,441 --> 00:26:36,761
DOCTOR: Took that long
to think of photographing it?

546
00:26:38,841 --> 00:26:40,361
You'd already memorised it, hadn't you?

547
00:26:40,441 --> 00:26:43,041
-Yep.
-Stop trying to keep me out of trouble.

548
00:26:44,601 --> 00:26:46,601
There's no trouble. (GRUNTS)

549
00:26:47,881 --> 00:26:50,041
This is going to be
a stroll in the park.

550
00:26:50,161 --> 00:26:51,281
(GRUNTING)

551
00:26:51,361 --> 00:26:52,361
(PANTING)

552
00:27:41,441 --> 00:27:42,561
(GASPS)

553
00:27:51,761 --> 00:27:52,921
(BEEPS)

554
00:28:24,201 --> 00:28:26,521
BILL: Doctor, why did people come here?

555
00:28:27,681 --> 00:28:29,241
Did something terrible happen?

556
00:28:29,601 --> 00:28:30,721
I can't hear you.

557
00:28:30,801 --> 00:28:32,521
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

558
00:28:33,641 --> 00:28:35,961
-(HISSING)
-Oh! Argh!

559
00:28:36,801 --> 00:28:39,681
-This isn't as easy as it looks.
-I've got to know.

560
00:28:40,001 --> 00:28:43,921
The people who came here.
Were they the last people?

561
00:28:44,721 --> 00:28:46,641
Were they our last hope?

562
00:28:46,961 --> 00:28:48,801
DOCTOR: Earth was evacuated.

563
00:28:53,561 --> 00:28:56,841
But there were a number of ships.

564
00:28:56,921 --> 00:28:59,321
I've bumped into a few of them
over the years.

565
00:28:59,401 --> 00:29:00,521
(ENGINE HUMMING LOUDLY)

566
00:29:00,601 --> 00:29:04,441
Right. I've rerouted the flow.

567
00:29:04,521 --> 00:29:06,761
-(RATTLING)
-No. No. No. No. No.

568
00:29:06,841 --> 00:29:08,281
That's not right. Bad noise.

569
00:29:08,361 --> 00:29:10,721
That's not right... No. No! Er...

570
00:29:11,041 --> 00:29:12,201
(GRUNTING)

571
00:29:15,121 --> 00:29:16,121
(GROANS)

572
00:29:18,521 --> 00:29:20,801
No. When the calorimeter
reaches its peak...

573
00:29:20,881 --> 00:29:22,521
I could do with a hand here!

574
00:29:22,601 --> 00:29:24,281
BILL: Okay. On my way.

575
00:29:25,521 --> 00:29:26,521
(GASPING)

576
00:29:32,521 --> 00:29:33,561
Oh.

577
00:29:34,001 --> 00:29:35,201
Are we there yet?

578
00:29:36,201 --> 00:29:37,361
(ALARM BLARING)

579
00:29:37,641 --> 00:29:39,921
BILL: Doctor,
there's something you need to know.

580
00:29:40,001 --> 00:29:42,721
I'm too busy! (GROANS)

581
00:29:47,321 --> 00:29:49,321
(ALARM BLARING)

582
00:29:49,481 --> 00:29:50,521
Oh!

583
00:29:54,761 --> 00:29:56,721
-(EMOJIBOT WARBLING)
-(DOCTOR STRAINING)

584
00:29:57,761 --> 00:29:58,921
(BOTH GASP)

585
00:30:01,001 --> 00:30:02,681
BILL: Almost with you, Doctor.

586
00:30:03,121 --> 00:30:04,961
You took your time.

587
00:30:05,281 --> 00:30:07,081
When I let this go,

588
00:30:07,201 --> 00:30:08,561
it's gonna spin back.

589
00:30:11,201 --> 00:30:13,401
I want you to hold it tight

590
00:30:13,481 --> 00:30:15,121
while I jam it shut.

591
00:30:15,201 --> 00:30:17,361
(EMOJIBOT CLICKING)

592
00:30:18,481 --> 00:30:19,601
(GRUNTS)

593
00:30:25,161 --> 00:30:27,561
-Doctor? Doctor, can you hear me?
-(DOCTOR GRUNTS)

594
00:30:27,681 --> 00:30:30,161
(GRUNTING) Oh, don't worry about me.

595
00:30:30,481 --> 00:30:32,161
I'm having the time of my life

596
00:30:32,281 --> 00:30:34,241
making new friends!

597
00:30:34,561 --> 00:30:35,601
Come on.

598
00:30:39,641 --> 00:30:40,761
(YELLS)

599
00:30:41,721 --> 00:30:43,201
(EMOJIBOT BLARES)

600
00:30:43,281 --> 00:30:44,361
(EXPLODES)

601
00:30:47,721 --> 00:30:49,401
-(GRUNTS)
-(ALARM BLARING)

602
00:30:50,041 --> 00:30:51,801
Get ready to run. Run really fast!

603
00:30:52,081 --> 00:30:53,601
(ALARM BLARING RAPIDLY)

604
00:30:54,361 --> 00:30:55,441
What?

605
00:30:56,761 --> 00:30:57,881
Where did you come from?

606
00:30:58,001 --> 00:30:59,361
Where is everybody?

607
00:31:00,721 --> 00:31:02,841
When you say everybody...

608
00:31:03,361 --> 00:31:05,201
WOMAN: (ON PA) My very good people.

609
00:31:05,281 --> 00:31:08,601
We will soon be beginning
an emergency disembarkation.

610
00:31:08,681 --> 00:31:11,921
Good people,
please prepare for disembarkation.

611
00:31:12,041 --> 00:31:13,481
(PODS ACTIVATING)

612
00:31:13,561 --> 00:31:15,801
We wish you a happy new world.

613
00:31:15,921 --> 00:31:17,081
Doctor?

614
00:31:17,841 --> 00:31:18,841
Pods.

615
00:31:19,761 --> 00:31:21,161
Pods.

616
00:31:21,241 --> 00:31:22,841
What is it? What's happening?

617
00:31:24,481 --> 00:31:26,161
We can't blow up the city.

618
00:31:26,241 --> 00:31:28,001
(ALARM CONTINUES BLARING)

619
00:31:29,201 --> 00:31:30,241
BILL: Why?

620
00:31:30,361 --> 00:31:32,241
Those pods, what's in them?

621
00:31:32,321 --> 00:31:33,601
I got it wrong.

622
00:31:34,721 --> 00:31:37,481
I got it very, very wrong.

623
00:31:40,441 --> 00:31:42,161
The colony ship isn't on the way.

624
00:31:42,561 --> 00:31:43,641
It's right here.

625
00:31:45,121 --> 00:31:47,041
The colonists are all around us.

626
00:31:47,121 --> 00:31:48,281
Cryogenically frozen.

627
00:31:48,361 --> 00:31:53,041
What's in those pods, Bill,
is the surviving population

628
00:31:53,121 --> 00:31:54,241
of Earth.

629
00:31:56,961 --> 00:31:58,721
And I nearly killed all of them.

630
00:31:59,361 --> 00:32:01,561
WOMAN: (ON PA)
Welcome to your new world.

631
00:32:01,641 --> 00:32:02,761
Be happy.

632
00:32:03,601 --> 00:32:05,121
BILL: 7hey're waking up, aren't they?

633
00:32:05,241 --> 00:32:07,201
We must've triggered the process
when we came in.

634
00:32:10,241 --> 00:32:11,641
So what happens now?

635
00:32:12,641 --> 00:32:13,921
Now?

636
00:32:15,721 --> 00:32:17,721
Now they're all gonna leave the ship

637
00:32:17,801 --> 00:32:20,441
and find their friends and family
mulched in the garden.

638
00:32:22,761 --> 00:32:24,481
And did Earth smile about that?

639
00:32:26,361 --> 00:32:28,401
It's going to be the end
of the human race.

640
00:32:41,201 --> 00:32:44,121
Argh. Oh, those pods, eh? (CHUCKLES)

641
00:32:44,201 --> 00:32:45,481
Not much headroom.

642
00:32:45,561 --> 00:32:47,401
Oh. Thought I'd be first up.

643
00:32:47,521 --> 00:32:48,961
Steadfast. I'm at Tech one.

644
00:32:49,081 --> 00:32:51,521
-What day is this?
-The end of the world.

645
00:32:51,601 --> 00:32:53,641
Again? We've only just got here.

646
00:32:54,761 --> 00:32:56,001
Bill, with me.

647
00:32:56,081 --> 00:32:57,161
What's happening?

648
00:32:58,801 --> 00:33:02,041
What's happening is nobody leaves
this ship until I tell you otherwise.

649
00:33:02,401 --> 00:33:03,801
Clear? Nobody leaves.

650
00:33:06,881 --> 00:33:08,321
-Where are we going?
-No idea.

651
00:33:08,401 --> 00:33:10,241
But if I look purposeful,
they'll think I've got a plan.

652
00:33:10,361 --> 00:33:11,561
If they think I've got a plan,

653
00:33:11,641 --> 00:33:14,001
at least they won't try to
think of a plan themselves.

654
00:33:14,081 --> 00:33:15,801
But you don't have a plan?

655
00:33:15,881 --> 00:33:18,001
I don't know how to stop it
happening again.

656
00:33:18,081 --> 00:33:20,161
Because I can't figure out
why it happened last time.

657
00:33:20,241 --> 00:33:21,761
What made them do this?

658
00:33:22,521 --> 00:33:24,281
I think I need to show you something.

659
00:33:26,041 --> 00:33:30,001
WOMAN: (ON PA) Section A-34,
reanimation sequence commencing.

660
00:33:30,081 --> 00:33:31,441
(PODS ACTIVATING)

661
00:33:33,081 --> 00:33:34,321
DOCTOR: Spacecraft landed.

662
00:33:35,441 --> 00:33:37,921
Most of the colonists were
kept in cryogenic suspension.

663
00:33:38,321 --> 00:33:40,201
A few, the ones with skills...

664
00:33:40,281 --> 00:33:42,081
The best ones. The brave ones.

665
00:33:42,161 --> 00:33:43,801
They were woken

666
00:33:45,281 --> 00:33:47,801
to shepherd the little flocks
of vardi robots.

667
00:33:48,561 --> 00:33:51,001
She came here. She was happy.

668
00:33:52,801 --> 00:33:54,121
It was all going well.

669
00:33:56,481 --> 00:33:57,961
Those are the shepherds, aren't they?

670
00:33:59,241 --> 00:34:00,481
And they're all dead.

671
00:34:02,521 --> 00:34:04,521
If we rearrange this data

672
00:34:05,001 --> 00:34:07,081
to reflect the time of death,
what do we get?

673
00:34:09,881 --> 00:34:11,481
(BEEPING)

674
00:34:13,241 --> 00:34:14,241
That's her.

675
00:34:18,801 --> 00:34:21,281
This woman died.
There's no sign of violence.

676
00:34:21,361 --> 00:34:23,481
So you know, she just died
the way that humans do.

677
00:34:26,121 --> 00:34:27,401
Then a few more people died

678
00:34:28,161 --> 00:34:32,121
all at the same time and then
a lot more died just after.

679
00:34:32,241 --> 00:34:34,961
And then the rest.

680
00:34:35,041 --> 00:34:36,241
Dozens.

681
00:34:37,001 --> 00:34:39,121
A virus? A virus that went...

682
00:34:40,041 --> 00:34:41,201
Well, viral?

683
00:34:41,841 --> 00:34:43,681
Grief! Grief!

684
00:34:43,841 --> 00:34:45,401
Grief as plague.

685
00:34:45,481 --> 00:34:46,481
How?

686
00:34:47,001 --> 00:34:50,681
The vardies, well, their job
was to maintain happiness.

687
00:34:51,001 --> 00:34:53,961
At first that meant making sure
there was enough oxygen and water.

688
00:34:54,041 --> 00:34:56,681
That's what the badges
are meant to communicate.

689
00:34:57,321 --> 00:34:58,561
Satisfaction.

690
00:34:58,641 --> 00:35:00,441
A positive mental state.

691
00:35:01,121 --> 00:35:03,001
But the vardi are smart.

692
00:35:03,721 --> 00:35:04,721
They learn.

693
00:35:05,241 --> 00:35:06,721
Try to be good servants.

694
00:35:07,321 --> 00:35:12,001
So they expand the definition
of happiness until...

695
00:35:12,801 --> 00:35:13,961
She dies.

696
00:35:15,441 --> 00:35:18,481
No one had ever died here
before this lady.

697
00:35:18,561 --> 00:35:21,081
The vardies, they've never
heard of grief before.

698
00:35:21,961 --> 00:35:26,441
This place is all about hope
and the future and happiness.

699
00:35:26,521 --> 00:35:28,001
No one ever thought about the opposite.

700
00:35:28,081 --> 00:35:30,241
The vardies didn't know
what to do with it.

701
00:35:31,961 --> 00:35:36,561
They identified grief
as the enemy of happiness

702
00:35:36,641 --> 00:35:40,201
and everyone who was experiencing grief

703
00:35:40,281 --> 00:35:41,601
as a problem,

704
00:35:41,681 --> 00:35:43,081
-as...
-Compost.

705
00:35:43,161 --> 00:35:44,481
And all those dead people,

706
00:35:44,561 --> 00:35:46,521
well, you know, they had friends
and family, too, so...

707
00:35:46,601 --> 00:35:47,921
BILL: Even more compost.

708
00:35:48,001 --> 00:35:50,041
And so on, and so on and so on

709
00:35:50,161 --> 00:35:53,361
and what you get
is a whole, like, a grief tsunami.

710
00:35:53,441 --> 00:35:54,921
And all this took how long?

711
00:35:55,161 --> 00:35:56,401
One morning.

712
00:35:56,681 --> 00:35:58,641
All of these people
were slaughtered in a day.

713
00:35:59,721 --> 00:36:01,041
Slaughtered for their own good.

714
00:36:01,321 --> 00:36:02,921
Because the vardi think different.

715
00:36:03,161 --> 00:36:04,761
Like the magic haddock.

716
00:36:04,841 --> 00:36:07,281
Not bad, not good, just different.

717
00:36:07,401 --> 00:36:10,081
So what will happen when
the new people meet the robots?

718
00:36:21,521 --> 00:36:22,681
BILL: That's the boy.

719
00:36:23,641 --> 00:36:25,481
The first to wake up.
Where did you get this?

720
00:36:25,561 --> 00:36:27,161
I think it's his mother's, don't you?

721
00:36:27,241 --> 00:36:28,321
Yeah, or his nan's.

722
00:36:29,921 --> 00:36:32,001
Well, you'll find her.
When she wakes up in her pod.

723
00:36:32,881 --> 00:36:35,561
I found it in the fruit garden
when we first arrived.

724
00:36:37,721 --> 00:36:38,801
Oh.

725
00:36:38,921 --> 00:36:43,001
I would say that a lot of the colonists
had friends or family

726
00:36:43,281 --> 00:36:44,921
who were working here as shepherds.

727
00:36:45,001 --> 00:36:46,321
When they find out what happened...

728
00:36:46,401 --> 00:36:48,561
They'll be grief-stricken.

729
00:36:49,521 --> 00:36:50,601
And after that?

730
00:36:51,121 --> 00:36:52,441
A massacre.

731
00:36:57,201 --> 00:36:58,521
Okay, where are we going?

732
00:36:58,601 --> 00:36:59,961
What's the opposite of a massacre?

733
00:37:01,041 --> 00:37:03,761
-Okay, what?
-In my experience a lecture.

734
00:37:14,201 --> 00:37:16,041
You brought the vardi here.

735
00:37:16,881 --> 00:37:20,321
Microbots to make your life so easy.

736
00:37:20,401 --> 00:37:22,881
But like every slave class in history,

737
00:37:22,961 --> 00:37:25,841
the vardi are beginning to have
ideas of their own.

738
00:37:27,201 --> 00:37:29,201
They wanted to eliminate unhappiness

739
00:37:29,281 --> 00:37:32,921
but to a robot that meant
eliminating unhappy people.

740
00:37:33,441 --> 00:37:35,521
They gave you monitors, badges,

741
00:37:35,761 --> 00:37:38,561
so they'd know when you were
too unhappy to live.

742
00:37:38,641 --> 00:37:39,761
(BEEPING)

743
00:37:46,161 --> 00:37:47,601
(RATTLING)

744
00:37:50,281 --> 00:37:52,281
-BILL: You need to listen.
- I did listen.

745
00:37:52,401 --> 00:37:55,281
What did I miss?
The vardi have killed our families.

746
00:37:55,361 --> 00:37:56,761
But you need to understand
why that happened.

747
00:37:56,841 --> 00:37:57,961
I don't care why.

748
00:37:58,041 --> 00:38:00,361
DOCTOR: Then you will die, too,
and so will everyone on your ship.

749
00:38:00,441 --> 00:38:02,761
-The vardi are not your enemy.
-They want to kill us.

750
00:38:02,841 --> 00:38:04,361
No, they want to help you.

751
00:38:04,441 --> 00:38:06,321
-Killing you is just the side effect.
-Get out of my way.

752
00:38:07,121 --> 00:38:10,321
You've got guns. You think that'll
help you against the whole living city?

753
00:38:10,761 --> 00:38:13,081
That little boy, where did he go?

754
00:38:13,681 --> 00:38:15,081
My mum was a gardener.

755
00:38:16,241 --> 00:38:17,441
Have you seen her?

756
00:38:18,481 --> 00:38:19,481
(EMOJIBOT GRUNTS)

757
00:38:20,721 --> 00:38:22,241
She's supposed to be here.

758
00:38:24,481 --> 00:38:26,161
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

759
00:38:32,441 --> 00:38:33,561
There he is.

760
00:38:34,081 --> 00:38:35,401
Step away from the kid.

761
00:38:35,481 --> 00:38:36,961
They're not armed.

762
00:38:37,041 --> 00:38:39,281
You don't need to do this.
You just need to...

763
00:38:39,361 --> 00:38:40,361
BOY: What's wrong?

764
00:38:41,401 --> 00:38:42,881
What's going on? Where's my mum?

765
00:38:43,801 --> 00:38:44,921
Where's everyone?

766
00:38:47,961 --> 00:38:50,041
-Where's everyone?
-Oh, no, no, no, no.

767
00:38:50,121 --> 00:38:51,121
Don't cry. Don't cry.

768
00:38:51,561 --> 00:38:52,561
Hey, hey...

769
00:38:53,001 --> 00:38:54,561
Look, everything's gonna be okay.

770
00:38:54,641 --> 00:38:56,401
Look.

771
00:38:56,481 --> 00:38:58,521
This is your new house. Isn't it lovely?

772
00:38:58,601 --> 00:38:59,681
I want Mummy.

773
00:38:59,761 --> 00:39:01,561
Okay. Smile, smile, smile, smile.

774
00:39:02,281 --> 00:39:04,041
Everything's gonna be fine
if you just keep smiling.

775
00:39:04,121 --> 00:39:05,481
Get away from the kid!

776
00:39:05,561 --> 00:39:06,561
(GUNS COCKING)

777
00:39:07,401 --> 00:39:08,481
-(BOY GROANS)
-(BILL GASPS)

778
00:39:09,241 --> 00:39:10,481
(CRACKLING)

779
00:39:11,521 --> 00:39:13,081
(EMOJIBOT BEEPING RAPIDLY)

780
00:39:13,681 --> 00:39:15,641
-What's that?
-(EMOJIBOT WARBLING)

781
00:39:16,201 --> 00:39:18,081
Rage? Revenge?

782
00:39:18,241 --> 00:39:19,521
It's one robot.

783
00:39:19,601 --> 00:39:20,961
It's not one robot.

784
00:39:22,921 --> 00:39:24,241
Doctor, what do we do?

785
00:39:24,321 --> 00:39:25,561
(ALL GASPING)

786
00:39:25,641 --> 00:39:26,801
Doctor, what's happening?

787
00:39:27,601 --> 00:39:28,601
STEADFAST: Cover fire! Now!

788
00:39:33,001 --> 00:39:34,841
-It's fascinating.
-What's fascinating?

789
00:39:34,921 --> 00:39:36,961
The vardi are identifying as
under attack.

790
00:39:37,041 --> 00:39:38,841
Which means they identify as a species.

791
00:39:39,041 --> 00:39:40,721
They are self-aware. They...

792
00:39:41,801 --> 00:39:42,841
They're alive!

793
00:39:43,321 --> 00:39:44,441
They're going to kill us.

794
00:39:44,561 --> 00:39:45,641
(MAN SCREAMS)

795
00:39:45,761 --> 00:39:47,321
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

796
00:39:48,721 --> 00:39:50,761
-What are you doing?
-I really hope this doesn't hurt.

797
00:39:51,721 --> 00:39:53,881
Do you know why I always win at chess?

798
00:39:54,561 --> 00:39:56,081
-Because I have a secret move.
-(GUNS FIRING)

799
00:39:56,641 --> 00:39:57,641
I kick over the board.

800
00:39:58,521 --> 00:39:59,521
Here it comes.

801
00:39:59,601 --> 00:40:00,681
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

802
00:40:00,841 --> 00:40:02,601
(EXPLOSION)

803
00:40:06,801 --> 00:40:09,401
DOCTOR: Once, long ago

804
00:40:09,481 --> 00:40:12,081
a fisherman caught a magic haddock.

805
00:40:12,161 --> 00:40:16,041
The haddock offered the fisherman
three wishes in return for his life.

806
00:40:17,041 --> 00:40:18,361
The fisherman said,

807
00:40:18,441 --> 00:40:20,961
"I'd like my son to come home
from the war

808
00:40:21,041 --> 00:40:22,961
"and 100 pieces of gold."

809
00:40:23,601 --> 00:40:27,841
The problem is magic haddock,
like robots,

810
00:40:28,001 --> 00:40:29,561
don't think like people.

811
00:40:29,761 --> 00:40:33,401
The fisherman's son came home
from the war in a coffin.

812
00:40:33,801 --> 00:40:38,201
The king sent 100 gold pieces
in recognition of his heroic death.

813
00:40:38,801 --> 00:40:42,921
The fisherman had one wish left.
What do you think he wished for?

814
00:40:43,561 --> 00:40:46,921
Some people say he should've wished
for an infinite series of wishes.

815
00:40:47,001 --> 00:40:49,281
But if your city proves anything,

816
00:40:49,361 --> 00:40:52,561
it is that granting all your wishes
is not a good idea.

817
00:40:52,641 --> 00:40:54,361
-(GRUNTS)
-BILL: It's okay.

818
00:40:54,841 --> 00:40:56,281
It's not gonna hurt you.

819
00:40:56,761 --> 00:40:58,321
Actually, he doesn't even know
who you are.

820
00:40:58,401 --> 00:41:00,281
What happened? What have you done?

821
00:41:00,361 --> 00:41:04,561
In fact, the fisherman wished that
he hadn't wished the first two wishes.

822
00:41:04,641 --> 00:41:06,721
Thus, in a way,
pressed the reset button.

823
00:41:07,441 --> 00:41:08,681
What the hell did you do?

824
00:41:10,161 --> 00:41:11,521
Aren't you listening?

825
00:41:11,961 --> 00:41:13,441
I pressed the reset button.

826
00:41:13,961 --> 00:41:16,481
Every computer has one
and anyone can find it.

827
00:41:16,561 --> 00:41:20,281
Especially if they happen to be
a scary, handsome, genius from space.

828
00:41:20,361 --> 00:41:22,561
I re-initialised the entire
command structure

829
00:41:23,121 --> 00:41:25,081
retaining all programmed abilities

830
00:41:25,161 --> 00:41:28,241
but deleting the supplementary
preference architecture.

831
00:41:29,041 --> 00:41:30,081
He turned it off and on again.

832
00:41:30,161 --> 00:41:31,881
DOCTOR:
I turned it off and on again.

833
00:41:35,041 --> 00:41:36,481
Course, I wiped their memories.

834
00:41:38,681 --> 00:41:41,321
They no longer have the faintest idea
who you are.

835
00:41:41,401 --> 00:41:44,641
And, in fact, they're wondering what
you're doing in their very nice city.

836
00:41:45,681 --> 00:41:46,721
Their city?

837
00:41:47,401 --> 00:41:48,401
Yes.

838
00:41:49,121 --> 00:41:50,201
Their city.

839
00:41:50,761 --> 00:41:51,761
It's made of them.

840
00:41:51,841 --> 00:41:53,201
-It's our city.
-Oh.

841
00:41:53,281 --> 00:41:55,401
-They're our robots.
-They were.

842
00:41:55,881 --> 00:41:57,081
DOCTOR: Welcome to your new world.

843
00:41:57,881 --> 00:41:59,081
Meet the vardi.

844
00:41:59,841 --> 00:42:03,041
They are as of now
the indigenous life form.

845
00:42:03,121 --> 00:42:04,481
You'd best make friends with them

846
00:42:04,561 --> 00:42:06,641
because there's loads of them.

847
00:42:06,721 --> 00:42:09,041
And they're the only ones who know
how anything works.

848
00:42:10,401 --> 00:42:11,401
They killed our people.

849
00:42:14,121 --> 00:42:15,281
Well, look.

850
00:42:16,361 --> 00:42:18,521
They have forgotten about that.

851
00:42:18,961 --> 00:42:20,761
They've forgotten about you.

852
00:42:21,081 --> 00:42:24,441
They've forgotten that you even
made them in the first place.

853
00:42:24,721 --> 00:42:27,441
Now, since they have absolute power
over this city

854
00:42:27,521 --> 00:42:31,521
and since, I'm assuming, you all
don't want to sleep rough tonight,

855
00:42:31,601 --> 00:42:32,681
I have a suggestion for you.

856
00:42:35,081 --> 00:42:36,081
BOTH: Smile.

857
00:42:37,441 --> 00:42:38,801
(CHUCKLES) You can't be serious.

858
00:42:39,041 --> 00:42:40,601
I am serious.

859
00:42:40,681 --> 00:42:42,481
In fact, I'm willing to be a negotiator.

860
00:42:42,561 --> 00:42:44,081
-Are you now?
-Yes.

861
00:42:45,041 --> 00:42:46,161
Watch.

862
00:42:46,961 --> 00:42:48,121
(EMOJIBOT BEEPS)

863
00:42:49,081 --> 00:42:51,161
Hello, I'm the Doctor.

864
00:42:52,201 --> 00:42:55,841
A few hours ago, I made the mistake
of not recognising your status

865
00:42:56,001 --> 00:42:58,201
as an emergent new life-form.

866
00:42:58,281 --> 00:43:02,761
As recompense for my mistake, please
allow me to act as your negotiator

867
00:43:02,841 --> 00:43:06,041
with the migratory conglomerate
known as the human race.

868
00:43:06,121 --> 00:43:09,081
They're looking for a place to stay
and they've got their eye on your city.

869
00:43:10,601 --> 00:43:11,921
(BEEPING)

870
00:43:12,121 --> 00:43:13,641
Would you like me to discuss rent?

871
00:43:13,721 --> 00:43:15,001
(TRILLING)

872
00:43:16,881 --> 00:43:18,081
(CASH REGISTER DINGS)

873
00:43:19,561 --> 00:43:21,321
BILL: So, ls it gonna work?

874
00:43:22,441 --> 00:43:23,721
DOCTOR: That's up to them.

875
00:43:26,921 --> 00:43:28,161
Did you just...

876
00:43:28,841 --> 00:43:31,041
Well, did we just

877
00:43:32,481 --> 00:43:34,081
jump start a new civilisation?

878
00:43:34,241 --> 00:43:36,041
It's a dirty job,
but someone's gotta do it.

879
00:43:36,281 --> 00:43:37,561
Did you do this all the time?

880
00:43:37,641 --> 00:43:38,721
Do what?

881
00:43:38,801 --> 00:43:40,601
Flying around sorting things out like
some kind of

882
00:43:40,681 --> 00:43:42,281
intergalactic policeman? (CHUCKLES)

883
00:43:42,361 --> 00:43:44,881
I don't sort things out.
I'm definitely not a policeman.

884
00:43:45,481 --> 00:43:47,041
Well, you live in a police box.

885
00:43:47,521 --> 00:43:50,161
-(SIGHS) It's a pure coincidence.
-Yeah, of course.

886
00:43:54,641 --> 00:43:57,121
Back at the exact moment we left.

887
00:43:58,201 --> 00:44:02,001
Kettle's boiling, and with
a vote to God,

888
00:44:02,081 --> 00:44:05,921
and everything is exactly as we left it.

889
00:44:09,201 --> 00:44:11,041
(WIND WHOOSHING)

890
00:44:11,121 --> 00:44:12,481
Wasn't snowing when we left.

891
00:44:12,961 --> 00:44:13,961
(GASPS)

892
00:44:17,281 --> 00:44:19,201
Maybe I do need a steering wheel.

893
00:44:21,441 --> 00:44:23,761
-BILL: Where are we?
-London.

894
00:44:26,441 --> 00:44:27,921
And this is

895
00:44:28,961 --> 00:44:29,961
the Thames.

896
00:44:31,361 --> 00:44:33,201
(TRUMPETING)

897
00:44:37,281 --> 00:44:38,881
(BELL TOLLING)

898
00:44:40,721 --> 00:44:42,601
BILL: 7ravel into the past,
there's got to be rules.

899
00:44:42,681 --> 00:44:44,961
If I step on a butterfly,
it could send ripples through time.

900
00:44:45,041 --> 00:44:46,761
-(MAN GRUNTS)
-Yeah!

901
00:44:46,841 --> 00:44:49,561
Regency England. Bit more black
than they show in the movies.

902
00:44:49,841 --> 00:44:51,441
Are there any side effects
to time travel?

903
00:44:52,201 --> 00:44:54,761
Sometimes you see lights under the ice.

904
00:44:54,841 --> 00:44:55,841
-(ICE CRACKS)
-Stay back!

905
00:44:55,921 --> 00:44:58,081
There's something frozen
under the Thames and it's eating people.

906
00:44:58,161 --> 00:44:59,481
Plan, let's get eaten.

907
00:44:59,561 --> 00:45:00,601
(YELLS)

908
00:45:02,241 --> 00:45:03,241
(GROWLS)

909
00:45:03,361 --> 00:45:05,241
MAN: The creature will be fed.

910
00:45:05,321 --> 00:45:06,721
Have you ever killed anyone?

